We are using photon vision to see the apriltags, but we are having problems because the raspberry pi disconects from photon vision and we notice a solid red light on the pi.

We already tried swaping power wires and our power source, also we already tried swaping cameras and camera’s cables but nothing seems to work.

I don’t know enough about electronics to say if that particular buck converter is problematic, but I do know that some are. Mostly being prone to brown outs if the main battery voltage drops.

You could try putting the pi on a different battery pack, just a lithium ion one, strap it down good, and see if that solves if the problem. If so… you know it’s power source.

The specifications of this DC-DC appear fine as long as your output is adjusted to 5.1V or thereabouts. Have you taken a MultiMeter and probed the output to see what its voltage is when the robot is powered ON?

Unfortunately the manufacturer of that device at least at the linked page does not publish transient behavior graphs or specifications, so the DC-DC could still be problematic, but on first inspection its performance I would expect to be acceptable as long as its set right and your wiring connections are solid. I would rule those out first before suspecting the DC-DC performance.

I would still advise caution with this, as there are many battery banks that can’t supply sufficient amperage.

The converter you linked does supply enough amperage, but again, we can’t be sure it functions with brownouts. To determine that, you could try running your robot and watching if battery drops coincide with cutouts in PV.

If you’re seeing the pi dying when here are brownouts, that indicates that your voltage converter isn’t able to supply enough power during brownouts. I would recommend getting a different converter, like this one from redux robotics.

Redux Robotics

Zinc-V 5V/4A Step-Down Regulator

12V input 5V 4A output DC-DC Step Down Regulator with terminal input and locking USB-C output for coprocessors and SBCs

Price: USD 20

It does appear to be sold out right now, so I would try to find a converter that can supply consistent power with voltage drops up to ~8V (or whatever your lowest brownout typically is at).
